  "districtId": "hall-of-knowledge",
  "body": "## Confirm replication health before touching anything else\n\nMany \"random\" Active Directory symptoms — inconsistent group membership, a password change that doesn't seem to take effect everywhere, a GPO that applies unevenly — trace back to replication issues between domain controllers. Checking replication health is usually the first step, before assuming the problem is anywhere else.\n\n## Isolate the layer: DNS, Kerberos, or the object itself\n\nAuthentication failures are rarely where they first appear to be. A methodical pass — is DNS resolving the right records, is time skew within Kerberos's tolerance, does the object itself have the attributes it should — finds the real layer faster than guessing from the error message alone, which is often generic.\n\n## Never make a directory-wide change without a rollback plan\n\nActive Directory changes have a wide blast radius by nature — a mistake in a GPO or a schema-adjacent change can affect every authenticated user at once. Any non-trivial change gets a written rollback step before it's made, and ideally gets tested against a single OU or test account first.\n\n## Legacy objects accumulate quietly\n\nStale computer objects, orphaned service accounts, and GPOs nobody remembers the purpose of build up over years in any sufficiently old directory. Periodic, careful cleanup — documented and reversible — keeps the environment auditable and makes the next real troubleshooting session faster, since there's less irrelevant clutter to rule out.\n\n## Document the fix, not just the symptom\n\nThe specific error message rarely repeats verbatim, but the underlying cause often does. A short, generalized note — what the symptom looked like, what the actual cause turned out to be, how it was confirmed — is more useful to a future self than a step-by-step log of the exact commands run that one time."
}
